{"title_page": "Daeg Faerch", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Daeg Faerch\n| image        = Faerch, Daeg (2007).jpg\n| caption      = Faerch at the [[2007 Scream Awards]]\n| birth_name   = Daeg Neergaard Faerch\n| birth_place  = [[San Diego, California|San Diego]], [[California]], U.S.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1995|9|27}}\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 2004\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Daeg Neergaard Faerch''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|e\u026a|\u0261|_|\u02c8|f|\u025b\u0259r|k}};<ref>Faerch says that his name is pronounced Day (''d\u0101'') with a 'G' at the end of it. Thus ''Day-g F-air-k.'' It is pronounced this way on the ''Halloween'' commentary and special features; it was also pronounced as this way on the 2007 Spike Scream Awards, on which Faerch was a presenter.</ref> born September 27, 1995)<ref>http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/daeg_neergaard_faerch_born_1995_23600752</ref><ref>https://familysearch.org/search/record/results?count=20&query=%2Bgivenname%3ADaeg~%20%2Bsurname%3AFaerch~%20%2Brecord_country%3A%22United%20States%22</ref> is an American actor. He is perhaps best known for his portrayal of young [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]] in [[Rob Zombie]]'s horror [[remake]] ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]'' (2007). Faerch has also played in theatrical productions of ''[[The Grapes of Wrath (play)|Grapes of Wrath]]'' in which he played the role of Winfield, ''[[Marat/Sade]]'' in which he played the role of young Herald, ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' playing the messenger, and ''Shakespeare Unabridged'' as a musical guest \u201drapper\". He has performed in [[Shakespeare]] productions, including ''[[Coriolanus (play)|Coriolanus]]'', in which he played young  Coriolanus, ''[[The Merry Wives of Windsor]]'', and ''[[Hamlet]]''. He also landed the role of Pincegurre in the French play ''L'Impromptu de Th\u00e9ophile'', as well as a role in the comedy ''The Nerd'', in which he played the character Thor Waldgrave.<ref name=\"Playhouse\">{{cite web| url=http://www.coronadoplayhouse.com/nerd/bios/daeg-faerch.html| title=Daeg Faerch| publisher=Coronado Playhouse.com| accessdate=2007-06-13| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070727021941/http://www.coronadoplayhouse.com/nerd/bios/daeg-faerch.html| archivedate=2007-07-27}}</ref> In addition to English, Faerch speaks French.\n\n==Career==\n\n===''Halloween''===\nAs a [[child actor]], Faerch was cast in the ''Halloween'' remake as a young Michael Myers, performing his own stunts.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7847 | title=Official Michael Myers Casting Confirmed! | publisher=Bloody Disgusting I | date=2006-12-19 | accessdate=2007-10-26 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080201174920/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7847 | archivedate=2008-02-01 }}</ref><ref name=\"THN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehollywoodnews.com/artman2/publish/movie_news/Interview_Daeg_Faerch_Tyler_Mane_for_Halloween_31280907.php |title=Interview: Daeg Faerch & Tyler Mane for Halloween |publisher=The Hollywood News |date=2007-09-28 |accessdate=2007-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018064051/http://thehollywoodnews.com/artman2/publish/movie_news/Interview_Daeg_Faerch_Tyler_Mane_for_Halloween_31280907.php |archivedate=2007-10-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"scary revealing\">{{cite web | url=http://lastheplace.com/2007/08/29/scary-revealing-rob-zombies-halloween-premieres-at-the-graumans-chinese-theatre/ | title=Scary Revealing: Rob Zombie's Halloween Premieres at Grauman's Chinese Theatre | publisher=The Last Place | date=2007-08-22 | accessdate=2008-02-01}}</ref>  Faerch's performance as the murderous young Myers was met with positive reviews. KPBS said of the young actor: \"Daeg Faerch is key in making these early scenes work. He delivers a truly chilling performance as a surprisingly sweet, soft and feminine looking ten-year-old Myers. His physical appearance contrasts with his brutal actions and it's only in his eyes that you perceive his true nature...Faerch\u2019s Myers can be like a normal kid one minute and a monster the next.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpbs.org/blogs/movies/2007/08/31/halloween/ |title=KPBS Movie Reviews >> Blog Archive >> Halloween |publisher=KPBS |date=2007-08-31 |accessdate=2007-11-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070923073517/http://www.kpbs.org/blogs/movies/2007/08/31/halloween/ |archivedate=2007-09-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Although Faerch was initially signed on to reprise his role as young Michael Myers in the sequel, ''[[Halloween II (2009 film)|Halloween II]]'' (then known as ''H2''), after filming briefly in Georgia as young Michael<ref>The scene appears in the movie pretrailer shown on ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]''(see [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EyWKJGKdztc YouTube clip]) and the newly released teaser trailer ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d3BHI0h1ees Youtube clip]).</ref> he was later recast because he had grown taller.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15466 | author=Mr. Disgusting | title=A New Young Michael Myers Arrives in Haddonfield | publisher=Bloody-Disgusting | date=2009-03-03 | accessdate=2009-03-05}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Chase Wright Vanek]].\n\n===Other projects===\nFaerch has a comedic role as a character named Michel in [[Peter Berg]]'s 2008 [[Will Smith]] film, ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvasia.com/News/200709/03014695.html |title=Will Smith Plays a homeless, flip-flop-wearing superhero in Hancock |publisher=MTV News |date=2007-09-03 |accessdate=2007-11-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070918182432/http://www.mtvasia.com/News/200709/03014695.html |archivedate=2007-09-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> where he plays a [[French American]] neighborhood boy who swears at Smith<ref name=\"THN\" /> and is thrown into the sky by the titular superhero for insulting him, but falls back to earth unharmed with Hancock catching him.\n\nFaerch's other projects include the thriller ''Sebastian'' in the title role, which also features his mother;<ref>{{IMDb title|1529568|Sebastian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sebastian \u2013 My new film |work=DaegFaerch.com |url=http://daegfaerch.com/blog/2009/10/29/sebastion-my-new-film/|accessdate=October 30, 2009}}</ref>\nthe [[Christmas]] comedy ''Wreck the Halls'' starring [[Mickey Rooney]] as [[Santa Claus]]; the short film \"[[Suffer the Little Children]]\", based on a story by [[Stephen King]] co-starring his mother.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1698761/ | title=Daeg Faerch \u2013 IMDb | publisher=IMDb | date= | accessdate=2008-06-07}}</ref> Faerch also performed in 2008 episodes of the TV show ''[[Pushing Daisies]]'', as a German schoolboy. He also recently co-starred as a [[homosexual]] young man named Jesse in the award-winning short film, ''Mental''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.eighteenmovie.com/director/mental| title=Mental - Dramatic short film| publisher=Eightenmovie.com| accessdate=2011-08-25| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823050922/http://eighteenmovie.com/director/mental| archivedate=2013-08-23}}</ref> On April 14, 2012, Faerch's 2010/2011 film ''Sebastian'' premiered at the Independent Film Quarterly (IFQ) Film and Webisode Festival, its only screening, where it also won Best [[Science fiction|Sci-Fi]] Feature.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://independentfilmquarterly.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=989&Itemid=159 | title=Los Angeles, April 2012 Awards | publisher=independentfilmquarterly.com | date= | accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref>\n\nA serious, near-fatal head injury and emergency surgery put Faerch's career on hold in 2012.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} In April 2013, Faerch and [[Kimberly J. Brown]] were attached to star in a science fiction thriller entitled ''Out There...'', to be directed by writer and [[Colorado]] native Bonn\u00e9 Bartron. It was to be filmed in Bartron's home state, and was originally to be funded through [[Kickstarter]], but failed to meet its $200,000 goal.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcoloradonews.com/news/bartron-to-film-in-colorado/article_5e6cc27a-a929-11e2-bd22-0019bb2963f4.html | title=Bartron to film in Colorado | author=Pat Hill | publisher=ourcoloradonews.com | date=2013-04-19 | accessdate=2013-04-21 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426014459/http://www.ourcoloradonews.com/news/bartron-to-film-in-colorado/article_5e6cc27a-a929-11e2-bd22-0019bb2963f4.html | archivedate=2013-04-26 }}</ref> Bartron then posted an update on Kickstarter, stating that she was taking the project to [[Indiegogo]] with flexible funding. According to Bartron, the campaign would be launched \"in the coming days.\"<ref name=\"Out There Indiegogo\">{{cite news|title=From the ashes rise a new opportunity|author=Bonn\u00e9 Bartron| publisher=Kickstarter.com|date=2013-04-30|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/angrypuppy/out-there-1/posts/467599|accessdate=2013-04-30}}</ref> However, this never happened, but the film has a page on [[FilmBreak]] The current status of the film is unknown as of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}.\n\nIn August 2014, Faerch's mother announced on Facebook that he would be taking a break from his rap \"career\" to film a role \"in the coming month.\" The project was later revealed to be '\"Ditch Party\"by the film's official Facebook page.<ref name=\"Ditch Party\">{{cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/ditchpartymovie | title=Ditch Party (official Facebook) | publisher=Facebook.com | date= | accessdate=2014-09-12}}</ref> The film was met with negative consensus. Filmthreat.com describes his role as \"he\u2019s an invisible presence for most of the first two acts, much-discussed but rarely encountered. That turns out to be for the better, because when he does finally cross paths with the holed-up main characters, he has a tendency toward monologues that wouldn\u2019t pass muster for a third-rate [[The Walking Dead (TV series)|Walking Dead]] villain\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/ditch-party/ | title=Ditch Party |FIlm Threat | publisher=filmthreat.com | date= | accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref>\n\nUpcoming projects for 2015 include the Christian [[American football|football]]/drug [[TV movie]] ''Lost in Oxyland'' as Dylan Jennings,<ref name=\"Lost in Oxyland\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3918238/ | title=Lost in Oxyland - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | date= | accessdate=2014-12-27}}</ref> the [[Daniel Baldwin]] Christian [[boxing]] drama ''Devotion'' as \"Paul the Bartender,\"<ref name=\"Devotion\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4167532/ | title=Devotion - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | date= | accessdate=2014-12-27}}</ref> the drug thriller ''[[The Glass Circle]]''  as \"The Weasel,\"<ref name=\"The Glass Circle\">{{cite web | url=https://twitter.com/StrongImageFilm/status/548595493555949568 | title=Strong Image Films (official Twitter) | publisher=Twitter.com | date=2014-12-26 | accessdate=2014-12-27}}</ref> a role in the [[Edward Furlong]] action-thriller ''Karma,''<ref name=\"Karma\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1762270/| title=Karma (IV) (2015) | publisher=IMDb.com | accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> a role in the thriller ''Amnesia,''<ref name=\"Amnesia\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4459124/ | title=Amnesia - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | accessdate=2015-04-14 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120224711/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt4459124/ | archivedate=2016-01-20 }}</ref> and the role of Devontae in the [[race (human classification)|race]]-drama ''[[Peterson Park]].''<ref name=\"Peterson Park\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4422778// | title=Peterson Park - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | date= | accessdate=2015-05-17}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, writer-director Edward Burney Jr. launched a [[Kickstarter]] campaign for ''Peterson Park,'' along with an official website.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.petersonparkthemovie.com/ | title=Peterson Park - Official Site | publisher=petersonparkthemovie.com | date= | accessdate=2015-06-14 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFaerch is featured in [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]]'s music video for \"[[Fun (Blondie song)|Fun]]\" from their 2017 album [[Pollinator (album)|''Pollinator'']].<ref>{{cite web|title=Blondie - Fun (official video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iEngbdIMZ6o|website=YouTube|publisher=BlondieVEVO|accessdate=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Acclaim==\nFaerch was named best minor character in [[Miami Herald]]'s 2008 Movie Yearbook for his role in ''Hancock''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.miamiherald.com/living/story/833128.html | title=2008 movie yearbook| author=Rene Rodriguez | publisher=Miami Herald | date=2009-01-02 | accessdate=2009-01-03}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nHorrorNews.net ranks Fearch in the all-time Top Ten Kids in Horror.<ref>http://www.horrornews.net/exclusives/html/Top_10_horror_child_stars.html</ref> Similarly, Fear Fragments.com ranks his Young Michael Myers as the No. 2 greatest \"evil kid\" performance in horror.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fearfragments.com/?p=13 |title=Evil Kid Movies |author=Stacey |publisher=Fear Fragments |date=2009-10-25 |accessdate=2010-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710234604/http://fearfragments.com/?p=13 |archivedate=July 10, 2011 }}</ref> 411Mania.com ranks Michael Myers as portrayed by Faerch and [[Tyler Mane]] as #5 on its list of the Top 8 Asylum Inmates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.411mania.com/movies/columns/228869 | title=The Top 8 Movie Asylum Inmates | author=Jeremy Thomas | publisher=411mania.com| date=2012-03-13 | accessdate=2012-05-27}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2004\n| ''Seafood Heaven''\n| Boy\n|\n|-\n| ''Jill''\n| Little Joshua\n|\n|-\n| ''Earl's Your Uncle''\n| Ratt\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2005\n| ''Frank's First Love''\n| Frank\n|\n|-\n| ''Andrew the Pirate''\n| Tom\n|\n|-\n| ''Life Ride''\n| Billy\n|\n|-\n| ''Lovin' Scoopful''\n| Bully #1\n|\n|-\n| ''Blind Doll''\n| Mute Child\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 2006\n| ''A Bullet Beyond Redemption''\n| Young Daniel\n|\n|-\n| ''Pedoefyl\u00e9''\n| Elvis Boy\n|\n|-\n| ''Angry Ghost''\n| Bernard\n|\n|-\n| ''Waiting Room''\n| Punk Kid\n|\n|-\n| ''Coming to Town''\n| Alasdair Romer\n|\n|-\n| ''Interminal''\n| Little Boy\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2007\n| ''Front''\n| Jason\n|\n|-\n| ''Lucky Numbers: A Musical''\n| Junior\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dark Mirror (2007 film)|Dark Mirror]]''\n| Neighbor Kid\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]''\n| Michael Myers (age 10)\n| a.k.a. Rob Zombie's Halloween\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 2008\n| ''The Liar''\n| Andy\n|\n|-\n| ''Wreck the Halls''\n| Charles\n|\n|-\n| ''Digits''\n| Matthew\n|\n|-\n| ''Villa Nova''\n| Brian\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]''\n| Michel\n| a.k.a. \"Hidden from Earth\" in the [[Philippines]]\n|-\n| ''Delaney''\n| Hercules\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Pushing Daisies]]''\n| Ingmar Todd\n| TV Series, 2 Episodes, \"Comfort Food\" & \"Dim Sum Lose Some\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2009\n| ''Family of Four''\n| Joshua\n|\n|-\n| ''Necromance''\n| David\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Run! Bitch Run!]]''\n| Tommy\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2010\n| ''Sebastian''\n| Sebastian\n|Premiered April 14, 2012 in Los Angeles<ref>{{cite news|title=IFQ: Sebastian|publisher=TicketWeb.com|date=2012-04-02|url=http://www.ticketweb.com/t3/sale/SaleEventDetail?dispatch=loadSelectionData&eventId=4484845|accessdate=2012-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=April 11-19, 2012 Press Release|publisher=IndependentFilmQuarterly.net|date=2012-04-10|url=http://independentfilmquarterly.net/press-coverage-2011/latus-14.html|accessdate=2012-04-10}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Mental''\n| Jesse\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n|''Ditch Party''<ref name=\"Ditch Party\"/>\n|The shooter<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4041916/ | title=Ditch Party - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | date= | accessdate=2014-12-27}}</ref>\n|Released and available on Amazon.com and [[Tubi]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://twitter.com/DitchPartyMovie/status/1084613697052368896| title=DITCH PARTY has just been added to @Tubi, a free streaming service that provides more than 8,500 titles, including #movies and TV shows coming from studios!  | publisher=Ditch Party Movie Official Twitter | date=2019-01-13 | accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|''Josie''\n|Gator\n|Available on Amazon.com and [[Blu-ray]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Josie-Blu-ray/199040/| title=Josie (2017) | publisher=Blu-ray.com | date=2018-06-03 | accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1698761}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faerch, Daeg}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Diego]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Daeg Faerch\n| image        = Faerch, Daeg (2007).jpg\n| caption      = Faerch at the [[2007 Scream Awards]]\n| birth_name   = Daeg Neergaard Faerch\n| birth_place  = [[San Diego, California|San Diego]], [[California]], U.S.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1995|9|27}}\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 2004\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Daeg Neergaard Faerch''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|e\u026a|\u0261|_|\u02c8|f|\u025b\u0259r|k}};<ref>Faerch says that his name is pronounced Day (''d\u0101'') with a 'G' at the end of it. Thus ''Day-g F-air-k.'' It is pronounced this way on the ''Halloween'' commentary and special features; it was also pronounced as this way on the 2007 Spike Scream Awards, on which Faerch was a presenter.</ref> born September 27, 1995)<ref>http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/daeg_neergaard_faerch_born_1995_23600752</ref><ref>https://familysearch.org/search/record/results?count=20&query=%2Bgivenname%3ADaeg~%20%2Bsurname%3AFaerch~%20%2Brecord_country%3A%22United%20States%22</ref> is an American actor. He is perhaps best known for his portrayal of young [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]] in [[Rob Zombie]]'s horror [[remake]] ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]'' (2007). Faerch has also played in theatrical productions of ''[[The Grapes of Wrath (play)|Grapes of Wrath]]'' in which he played the role of Winfield, ''[[Marat/Sade]]'' in which he played the role of young Herald, ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' playing the messenger, and ''Shakespeare Unabridged'' as a musical guest \u201drapper\". He has performed in [[Shakespeare]] productions, including ''[[Coriolanus (play)|Coriolanus]]'', in which he played young  Coriolanus, ''[[The Merry Wives of Windsor]]'', and ''[[Hamlet]]''. He also landed the role of Pincegurre in the French play ''L'Impromptu de Th\u00e9ophile'', as well as a role in the comedy ''The Nerd'', in which he played the character Thor Waldgrave.<ref name=\"Playhouse\">{{cite web| url=http://www.coronadoplayhouse.com/nerd/bios/daeg-faerch.html| title=Daeg Faerch| publisher=Coronado Playhouse.com| accessdate=2007-06-13| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070727021941/http://www.coronadoplayhouse.com/nerd/bios/daeg-faerch.html| archivedate=2007-07-27}}</ref> In addition to English, Faerch speaks French.\n\n==Career==\n\n===''Halloween''===\nAs a [[child actor]], Faerch was cast in the ''Halloween'' remake as a young Michael Myers, performing his own stunts.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7847 | title=Official Michael Myers Casting Confirmed! | publisher=Bloody Disgusting I | date=2006-12-19 | accessdate=2007-10-26 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080201174920/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7847 | archivedate=2008-02-01 }}</ref><ref name=\"THN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehollywoodnews.com/artman2/publish/movie_news/Interview_Daeg_Faerch_Tyler_Mane_for_Halloween_31280907.php |title=Interview: Daeg Faerch & Tyler Mane for Halloween |publisher=The Hollywood News |date=2007-09-28 |accessdate=2007-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018064051/http://thehollywoodnews.com/artman2/publish/movie_news/Interview_Daeg_Faerch_Tyler_Mane_for_Halloween_31280907.php |archivedate=2007-10-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"scary revealing\">{{cite web | url=http://lastheplace.com/2007/08/29/scary-revealing-rob-zombies-halloween-premieres-at-the-graumans-chinese-theatre/ | title=Scary Revealing: Rob Zombie's Halloween Premieres at Grauman's Chinese Theatre | publisher=The Last Place | date=2007-08-22 | accessdate=2008-02-01}}</ref>  Faerch's performance as the murderous young Myers was met with positive reviews. KPBS said of the young actor: \"Daeg Faerch is key in making these early scenes work. He delivers a truly chilling performance as a surprisingly sweet, soft and feminine looking ten-year-old Myers. His physical appearance contrasts with his brutal actions and it's only in his eyes that you perceive his true nature...Faerch\u2019s Myers can be like a normal kid one minute and a monster the next.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpbs.org/blogs/movies/2007/08/31/halloween/ |title=KPBS Movie Reviews >> Blog Archive >> Halloween |publisher=KPBS |date=2007-08-31 |accessdate=2007-11-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070923073517/http://www.kpbs.org/blogs/movies/2007/08/31/halloween/ |archivedate=2007-09-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Although Faerch was initially signed on to reprise his role as young Michael Myers in the sequel, ''[[Halloween II (2009 film)|Halloween II]]'' (then known as ''H2''), after filming briefly in Georgia as young Michael<ref>The scene appears in the movie pretrailer shown on ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]''(see [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EyWKJGKdztc YouTube clip]) and the newly released teaser trailer ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d3BHI0h1ees Youtube clip]).</ref> he was later recast because he had grown taller.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15466 | author=Mr. Disgusting | title=A New Young Michael Myers Arrives in Haddonfield | publisher=Bloody-Disgusting | date=2009-03-03 | accessdate=2009-03-05}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Chase Wright Vanek]].\n\n===Other projects===\nFaerch has a comedic role as a character named Michel in [[Peter Berg]]'s 2008 [[Will Smith]] film, ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvasia.com/News/200709/03014695.html |title=Will Smith Plays a homeless, flip-flop-wearing superhero in Hancock |publisher=MTV News |date=2007-09-03 |accessdate=2007-11-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070918182432/http://www.mtvasia.com/News/200709/03014695.html |archivedate=2007-09-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> where he plays a [[French American]] neighborhood boy who swears at Smith<ref name=\"THN\" /> and is thrown into the sky by the titular superhero for insulting him, but falls back to earth unharmed with Hancock catching him.\n\nFaerch's other projects include the thriller ''Sebastian'' in the title role, which also features his mother;<ref>{{IMDb title|1529568|Sebastian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sebastian \u2013 My new film |work=DaegFaerch.com |url=http://daegfaerch.com/blog/2009/10/29/sebastion-my-new-film/|accessdate=October 30, 2009}}</ref>\nthe [[Christmas]] comedy ''Wreck the Halls'' starring [[Mickey Rooney]] as [[Santa Claus]]; the short film \"[[Suffer the Little Children]]\", based on a story by [[Stephen King]] co-starring his mother.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1698761/ | title=Daeg Faerch \u2013 IMDb | publisher=IMDb | date= | accessdate=2008-06-07}}</ref> Faerch also performed in 2008 episodes of the TV show ''[[Pushing Daisies]]'', as a German schoolboy. He also recently co-starred as a [[homosexual]] young man named Jesse in the award-winning short film, ''Mental''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.eighteenmovie.com/director/mental| title=Mental - Dramatic short film| publisher=Eightenmovie.com| accessdate=2011-08-25| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823050922/http://eighteenmovie.com/director/mental| archivedate=2013-08-23}}</ref> On April 14, 2012, Faerch's 2010/2011 film ''Sebastian'' premiered at the Independent Film Quarterly (IFQ) Film and Webisode Festival, its only screening, where it also won Best [[Science fiction|Sci-Fi]] Feature.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://independentfilmquarterly.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=989&Itemid=159 | title=Los Angeles, April 2012 Awards | publisher=independentfilmquarterly.com | date= | accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref>\n\nA serious, near-fatal head injury and emergency surgery put Faerch's career on hold in 2012.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} In April 2013, Faerch and [[Kimberly J. Brown]] were attached to star in a science fiction thriller entitled ''Out There...'', to be directed by writer and [[Colorado]] native Bonn\u00e9 Bartron. It was to be filmed in Bartron's home state, and was originally to be funded through [[Kickstarter]], but failed to meet its $200,000 goal.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcoloradonews.com/news/bartron-to-film-in-colorado/article_5e6cc27a-a929-11e2-bd22-0019bb2963f4.html | title=Bartron to film in Colorado | author=Pat Hill | publisher=ourcoloradonews.com | date=2013-04-19 | accessdate=2013-04-21 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426014459/http://www.ourcoloradonews.com/news/bartron-to-film-in-colorado/article_5e6cc27a-a929-11e2-bd22-0019bb2963f4.html | archivedate=2013-04-26 }}</ref> Bartron then posted an update on Kickstarter, stating that she was taking the project to [[Indiegogo]] with flexible funding. According to Bartron, the campaign would be launched \"in the coming days.\"<ref name=\"Out There Indiegogo\">{{cite news|title=From the ashes rise a new opportunity|author=Bonn\u00e9 Bartron| publisher=Kickstarter.com|date=2013-04-30|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/angrypuppy/out-there-1/posts/467599|accessdate=2013-04-30}}</ref> However, this never happened, but the film has a page on [[FilmBreak]] The current status of the film is unknown as of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}.\n\nIn August 2014, Faerch's mother announced on Facebook that he would be taking a break from his rap \"career\" to film a role \"in the coming month.\" The project was later revealed to be '\"Ditch Party\"by the film's official Facebook page.<ref name=\"Ditch Party\">{{cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/ditchpartymovie | title=Ditch Party (official Facebook) | publisher=Facebook.com | date= | accessdate=2014-09-12}}</ref> The film was met with negative consensus. Filmthreat.com describes his role as \"he\u2019s an invisible presence for most of the first two acts, much-discussed but rarely encountered. That turns out to be for the better, because when he does finally cross paths with the holed-up main characters, he has a tendency toward monologues that wouldn\u2019t pass muster for a third-rate Walking Dead villain\"\n\nUpcoming projects for 2015 include the Christian [[American football|football]]/drug [[TV movie]] ''Lost in Oxyland'' as Dylan Jennings,<ref name=\"Lost in Oxyland\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3918238/ | title=Lost in Oxyland - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | date= | accessdate=2014-12-27}}</ref> the [[Daniel Baldwin]] Christian [[boxing]] drama ''Devotion'' as \"Paul the Bartender,\"<ref name=\"Devotion\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4167532/ | title=Devotion - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | date= | accessdate=2014-12-27}}</ref> the drug thriller ''[[The Glass Circle]]''  as \"The Weasel,\"<ref name=\"The Glass Circle\">{{cite web | url=https://twitter.com/StrongImageFilm/status/548595493555949568 | title=Strong Image Films (official Twitter) | publisher=Twitter.com | date=2014-12-26 | accessdate=2014-12-27}}</ref> a role in the [[Edward Furlong]] action-thriller ''Karma,''<ref name=\"Karma\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1762270/| title=Karma (IV) (2015) | publisher=IMDb.com | accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> a role in the thriller ''Amnesia,''<ref name=\"Amnesia\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4459124/ | title=Amnesia - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | accessdate=2015-04-14 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120224711/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt4459124/ | archivedate=2016-01-20 }}</ref> and the role of Devontae in the [[race (human classification)|race]]-drama ''[[Peterson Park]].''<ref name=\"Peterson Park\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4422778// | title=Peterson Park - IMDb | publisher=IMDb.com | date= | accessdate=2015-05-17}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, writer-director Edward Burney Jr. launched a [[Kickstarter]] campaign for ''Peterson Park,'' along with an official website.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.petersonparkthemovie.com/ | title=Peterson Park - Official Site | publisher=petersonparkthemovie.com | date= | accessdate=2015-06-14 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFaerch is featured in [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]]'s music video for \"[[Fun (Blondie song)|Fun]]\" from their 2017 album [[Pollinator (album)|''Pollinator'']].<ref>{{cite web|title=Blondie - Fun (official video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iEngbdIMZ6o|website=YouTube|publisher=BlondieVEVO|accessdate=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Acclaim==\nFaerch was named best minor character in [[Miami Herald]]'s 2008 Movie Yearbook for his role in ''Hancock''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.miamiherald.com/living/story/833128.html | title=2008 movie yearbook| author=Rene Rodriguez | publisher=Miami Herald | date=2009-01-02 | accessdate=2009-01-03}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nHorrorNews.net ranks Fearch in the all-time Top Ten Kids in Horror.<ref>http://www.horrornews.net/exclusives/html/Top_10_horror_child_stars.html</ref> Similarly, Fear Fragments.com ranks his Young Michael Myers as the No. 2 greatest \"evil kid\" performance in horror.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fearfragments.com/?p=13 |title=Evil Kid Movies |author=Stacey |publisher=Fear Fragments |date=2009-10-25 |accessdate=2010-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710234604/http://fearfragments.com/?p=13 |archivedate=July 10, 2011 }}</ref> 411Mania.com ranks Michael Myers as portrayed by Faerch and [[Tyler Mane]] as #5 on its list of the Top 8 Asylum Inmates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.411mania.com/movies/columns/228869 | title=The Top 8 Movie Asylum Inmates | author=Jeremy Thomas | publisher=411mania.com| date=2012-03-13 | accessdate=2012-05-27}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2004\n| ''Seafood Heaven''\n| Boy\n|\n|-\n| ''Jill''\n| Little Joshua\n|\n|-\n| ''Earl's Your Uncle''\n| Ratt\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2005\n| ''Frank's First Love''\n| Frank\n|\n|-\n| ''Andrew the Pirate''\n| Tom\n|\n|-\n| ''Life 